{[ROLE leader][STAGE pre-lead] Lead the \S2. With nothing screaming to be led, fourth-best from your longest suit is the standard, safe choice against this part-score.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE auction-end] You are North in 3\H. Trumps are solid for five tricks, \S gives you four cashing winners on top, and \D supplies two more (\DA plus the \DK) — that already meets the contract. The extra trick, and the lesson, is the two-way guess for the \DQ: you hold \DAJ4 opposite \DKT5, so you can finesse East for the queen (low to your jack) OR finesse West (low to dummy's ten). West bid clubs along the way, so file that count away before you guess.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-lead] West led the \S2 — a fourth-best spot, so the long spades and any club length both sit with West. West's club bidding marks a long club suit over there, which means West has fewer cards left for the red suits; East has the room. Win, draw trumps, then run the diamond toward your \DJ, finessing East for the \DQ, because the player who is short in clubs (East) has the empty spaces where the queen is more likely to live. If the jack holds, you have your overtrick; if it loses, your line was still the percentage one.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-play] The club length West advertised was the whole clue: long clubs over there meant short diamonds, so the queen rated to be with East — exactly where finessing the jack catches it. Nicely reasoned; you let the auction place the card instead of flipping a coin.}
